# Components Used

## Hardware Components

### Arduino Uno
Main microcontroller used for executing the PID control algorithm, reading encoder feedback, and generating PWM signals for motor control.

### BTS7960 Motor Driver
High-current motor driver module used to drive the DC motor using PWM control signals from the Arduino.

### N20 Encoder DC Motor
12V geared DC motor with integrated encoder used for rotational feedback and closed-loop control.

### Breadboard
Used for temporary prototyping, signal routing, pull-up resistor connections, and capacitor placement.

### 12V DC Power Adapter
External power source used to supply power to the motor driver and DC motor.

### Jumper Wires
Used for electrical interconnections between Arduino, encoder, breadboard, and motor driver.

### 10kΩ Pull-Up Resistors
Connected to encoder signal lines to stabilize pulse readings and prevent floating signals.

### 0.1µF Ceramic Capacitor
Used near encoder power lines for filtering high-frequency electrical noise generated during motor operation.

### 100µF Electrolytic Capacitor
Connected across motor terminals to suppress voltage spikes and reduce motor noise.


# Software Used

- Arduino IDE
- Embedded C/C++
- Serial Monitor for debugging and PID tuning
